text: The pluramycins constitute a family of antibiotics featured by the polyketide-derived anthrapyranotrione  chromophore containing two amino C-glycosides.1 Pluramycin A (1), reported in 1956 by Umezawa and  Kondo  et  al.,  is  the  first  member  of  this  class,  which  was  isolated  from  a  terrestrial  Streptomyces  sp.2  Since  then,  many  related  compounds  have  appeared,  including  kidamycin  (2),3  hedamycin  (3),4  and  saptomycin B (4)5 (Figure 1). The potent antitumor activity exhibited by several of these compounds has  Dedicated to Professor Isao Kuwajima on occasion of his 77th birthday DIHYDROXYANTHRONE TRICYCLIC PLATFORM TO AN AGLYCON,  Kei  Kitamura,1  Yoshio  Ando, 1 Yoshihiko  Maezawa,1  Takashi  Matsumoto,2*  and Keisuke Suzuki1*  1Department  of  Chemistry,  Tokyo  Institute  of  Technology,  2-12-1  O-okayama,  Meguro-ku,  Tokyo  152-8551,  Japan.  2 School  of  Pharmacy,  Tokyo  University  of  antibiotics,  we  recently  found  dihydroxyanthrone  derivatives  to  be  suitable  platforms for the installation of bis-C-glycosides. As a basis for the total synthesis,  we  explored  viable  routes  to  construct  the  characteristic  tetracyclic  skeleton.  By  setting saptomycinone B (5) as a model target, anthrone 6 was combined with the  side chain moiety to access key intermediate 9, from which two viable routes have  been  developed.  One  of  the  routes  has  been  exploited  in  the  realization  of  our  recent total synthesis of saptomycin B (4).
